u can?" And "How do they say 'Hounyhnhnm' and 'Cheshire Cat' and things like that in German?" And, in either language, "How, in God's name, can you possibly say 'There she blows!'?" This book, unfortunately left incomplete on his death in 1966, contains many of his answers. They are given not only in the assembled texts and translations but also in his wry, curious, sometimes hilarious commentaries. None of it is scholarly in any formal, academic sense—"and yet," Reid reminds us, "his is precisely the kind of enthusiastic curiosity that gives scholarship its pointers."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh1 aNagel, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNagel, Charles.1 aReid, Alastair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Alistair.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70116840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292758285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292758285/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK